Note:
LLVM IR (textual .ll) Translation Round-Trip Probe

End-to-end proof that the LLVM IR translation pipeline is REAL, not a skeleton:

    LLVM IR textual source
      -> create_llvmir_lexer   (wrap source; the parser drives next_token which
                                tokenizes keywords (define/ret/add/...), value
                                types (i32/...), @global / %local identifiers,
                                numbers, strings, and single-character punctuation
                                with NUL-terminated owned lexemes)
      -> create_llvm_parser    (one-token-lookahead recursive-descent parser; each
                                construct builds an LLVMNode tagged LLVM_MODULE,
                                LLVM_FUNCTION, LLVM_BASIC_BLOCK, LLVM_INSTRUCTION,
                                LLVM_TYPE, LLVM_VALUE, or LLVM_GLOBAL)
      -> parse_module          (top-level entry: functions/declares/globals/types/
                                target/attributes)
      -> translate_llvmir_to_hir  (project the LLVMNode tree into the HIR
                                dictionary/list-literal model; module ->
                                {_type:"llvm_module", functions:[...]}, function ->
                                {_type:"llvm_function", name, return_type,
                                basic_blocks:[...]}, basic_block ->
                                {_type:"llvm_basic_block", label, instructions:[...]},
                                instruction -> {_type:"llvm_instruction", opcode,
                                result?, operands:[string...]})
      -> generate_llvmir       (emit the HIR dictionary back to canonical LLVM IR
                                text)

The HIR model is the dictionary/list-literal model (raw string-keyed entries on a
HIR_DICTIONARY_LITERAL node), NOT the typed hir.runa tree. Every accessor in this
probe reads the dictionary structure directly via get_dictionary_entries +
string_equals on entry keys (the same read contract the backend uses), and reads
leaf values via get_string_literal_value and list contents via get_list_elements.

The probe feeds a representative LLVM IR snippet:

    define i32 @add(i32 %a, i32 %b) {
    entry:
      %r = add i32 %a, %b
      ret i32 %r
    }

exercising: a define with a return type and @-name, a named basic block label, a
result-assigning binary instruction (%r = add i32 %a, %b) whose operands are the
type "i32" and the two register values "%a"/"%b", and a terminator (ret i32 %r).

It then:
  1. Drives the source through lexer -> parser -> to_hir and asserts the HIR
     dictionary _type tag and the top-level function count.
  2. Asserts the lowered function name, return type, basic-block label, and the
     two instructions' opcodes / result registers / operand streams survived on
     the FIRST emission's HIR.
  3. Emits the HIR back to LLVM IR text and asserts the text is non-empty.
  4. Re-parses the emitted text back into HIR (the SECOND emission) and asserts
     the two HIR streams are STRUCTURALLY EQUAL via recursive comparators: same
     function count, and per-function the same name / return type / basic-block
     stream (label + per-instruction opcode + result + operand string stream) at
     every position. The backend canonicalises whitespace and folded forms, so the
     byte stream differs while the meaning is identical; structural equality is the
     correct fidelity check.

Exit code: number of failed assertions (0 == all passed). No exit_with_code.
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/llvmir/llvmir_lexer.runa" as LlvmLexer
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/llvmir/llvmir_parser.runa" as LlvmParser
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/llvmir/llvmir_to_hir.runa" as LlvmFrontend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/llvmir/hir_to_llvmir.runa" as LlvmBackend
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/hir.runa" as HIR
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "tests/test_utils.runa" as TestUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Pipeline driver: LLVM IR source -> HIR dictionary
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The LLVM IR pipeline has no single source-to-HIR convenience, so the probe owns
the chain explicitly: create_llvmir_lexer wraps the source, create_llvm_parser
binds the lexer and pre-fetches the first token, parse_module builds the LLVMNode
AST, and translate_llvmir_to_hir projects it into the HIR dictionary. Returning the
dictionary pointer (or 0 on any stage failure) lets the caller assert on one value.
@End Reasoning
Process called "llvmir_source_to_hir" takes source as Integer returns Integer:
    Let lexer be proc create_llvmir_lexer from LlvmLexer with source
    If lexer is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let parser be proc create_llvm_parser from LlvmParser with lexer
    If parser is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse_module from LlvmParser with parser
    If ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc translate_llvmir_to_hir from LlvmFrontend with ast
    Return hir
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIR dictionary accessors (mirror the backend's read contract)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
The HIR dictionary literal stores entries as raw 16-byte [key(0), value(8)] blocks
whose keys are plain string pointers compared with string_equals — exactly the
contract get_dict_string_value / get_dict_hir_value use inside the backend. This
helper builds the key literal, scans the entries list, and returns the raw value
node (or 0 if absent) so the comparators and assertions read it uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_dict_get" takes node as Integer, key as String returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let entries be proc get_dictionary_entries from HIR with node
    If entries is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let key_str be proc create_from_literal from StringCore with key
    Let count be proc size from List with entries
    Let index be 0

    While index is less than count:
        Let entry be proc get_at from List with entries, index
        Let entry_key be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 0
        Let entry_value be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry, 8

        Let matches be proc string_equals from StringCore with key_str, entry_key
        If matches is equal to 1:
            Return entry_value
        End If

        Set index to index plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Convenience wrapper that fetches a dictionary entry and unwraps it as a string
literal value. The leaf fields in the LLVM IR HIR (name, return type, label,
opcode, result, operand) are all HIR string literals, so this returns the C-string
pointer for assert_string_equal / string_equals comparison.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_dict_get_string" takes node as Integer, key as String returns Integer:
    Let value be proc hir_dict_get with node, key
    If value is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with value
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns the number of elements in a HIR list literal, tolerating a missing (0)
list so count assertions read uniformly.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_list_count" takes lst as Integer returns Integer:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let items be proc get_list_elements from HIR with lst
    If items is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc size from List with items
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returns element i of a HIR list literal as a raw node pointer so callers can read
its dictionary fields.
@End Reasoning
Process called "hir_list_at" takes lst as Integer, index as Integer returns Integer:
    If lst is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let items be proc get_list_elements from HIR with lst
    If items is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Return proc get_at from List with items, index
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Structural equality comparators (recursive)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning:
Two operand streams are equal when they have the same length and the same string
value at every position. Frontend operands are HIR string literals (a type spelling
like "i32" or a value spelling like "%a"), so position-for-position string equality
is the right operand-level fidelity check.
@End Reasoning
Process called "operand_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc hir_list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc hir_list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let op_a be proc hir_list_at with a, i
        Let op_b be proc hir_list_at with b, i

        Let val_a be proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with op_a
        Let val_b be proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with op_b
        Let vals_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with val_a, val_b
        If vals_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two instructions are equal when their opcodes match, their result registers match
(both absent counts as a match), and their operand streams are equal. This is the
load-bearing per-instruction round-trip check.
@End Reasoning
Process called "instructions_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    If a is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If b is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let opcode_a be proc hir_dict_get_string with a, "opcode"
    Let opcode_b be proc hir_dict_get_string with b, "opcode"
    Let opcodes_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with opcode_a, opcode_b
    If opcodes_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Result register: compare presence first, then value when present.
    Let result_a be proc hir_dict_get with a, "result"
    Let result_b be proc hir_dict_get with b, "result"

    If result_a is equal to 0:
        If result_b is not equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If
    Otherwise:
        If result_b is equal to 0:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let res_str_a be proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with result_a
        Let res_str_b be proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with result_b
        Let results_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with res_str_a, res_str_b
        If results_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
    End If

    Let ops_a be proc hir_dict_get with a, "operands"
    Let ops_b be proc hir_dict_get with b, "operands"
    Let operands_match be proc operand_streams_equal with ops_a, ops_b
    If operands_match is not equal to 1:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two instruction streams are equal when they have the same length and structurally
equal instructions at every position.
@End Reasoning
Process called "instruction_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc hir_list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc hir_list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let instr_a be proc hir_list_at with a, i
        Let instr_b be proc hir_list_at with b, i
        Let match be proc instructions_equal with instr_a, instr_b
        If match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two basic-block streams are equal when they have the same length and, at every
position, the same label and structurally equal instruction streams.
@End Reasoning
Process called "basic_block_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc hir_list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc hir_list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let bb_a be proc hir_list_at with a, i
        Let bb_b be proc hir_list_at with b, i

        Let label_a be proc hir_dict_get_string with bb_a, "label"
        Let label_b be proc hir_dict_get_string with bb_b, "label"
        Let labels_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with label_a, label_b
        If labels_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let insts_a be proc hir_dict_get with bb_a, "instructions"
        Let insts_b be proc hir_dict_get with bb_b, "instructions"
        Let insts_match be proc instruction_streams_equal with insts_a, insts_b
        If insts_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Two function streams are equal when they have the same length and, at every
position, the same name, the same return type, and structurally equal basic-block
streams. This is the load-bearing whole-function round-trip check.
@End Reasoning
Process called "function_streams_equal" takes a as Integer, b as Integer returns Integer:
    Let count_a be proc hir_list_count with a
    Let count_b be proc hir_list_count with b
    If count_a is not equal to count_b:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than count_a:
        Let fa be proc hir_list_at with a, i
        Let fb be proc hir_list_at with b, i

        Let name_a be proc hir_dict_get_string with fa, "name"
        Let name_b be proc hir_dict_get_string with fb, "name"
        Let names_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with name_a, name_b
        If names_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let ret_a be proc hir_dict_get_string with fa, "return_type"
        Let ret_b be proc hir_dict_get_string with fb, "return_type"
        Let rets_match be proc string_equals from StringCore with ret_a, ret_b
        If rets_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Let bbs_a be proc hir_dict_get with fa, "basic_blocks"
        Let bbs_b be proc hir_dict_get with fb, "basic_blocks"
        Let bbs_match be proc basic_block_streams_equal with bbs_a, bbs_b
        If bbs_match is not equal to 1:
            Return 0
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Probe entry point
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Let results be proc create_test_results from TestUtils
    proc begin_suite from TestUtils with results, "LLVM IR translation round-trip"

    Note:
    Representative LLVM IR snippet. Newlines are explicit \n in the Runa string
    literal. "define"/"ret" are keywords; "add" is classified as a generic
    keyword identifier; "i32" is a value type; "@add" is a global id; "%a"/"%b"/
    "%r" are local ids; "entry" is the basic-block label.
    :End Note
    Let source be "define i32 @add(i32 %a, i32 %b) {\nentry:\n  %r = add i32 %a, %b\n  ret i32 %r\n}\n"

    Note: --- Stage 1: source -> HIR ---
    Let hir1 be proc llvmir_source_to_hir with source
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "pipeline produced HIR dictionary", hir1

    Let type_value be proc hir_dict_get_string with hir1, "_type"
    Let type_is_module be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_value, "llvm_module"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "HIR _type is llvm_module", type_is_module, 1

    Let functions1 be proc hir_dict_get with hir1, "functions"
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "HIR carries a functions section", functions1
    Let func_count1 be proc hir_list_count with functions1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "1 function parsed", func_count1, 1

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: function @add signature ---
    Let func0 be proc hir_list_at with functions1, 0
    Let func0_type be proc hir_dict_get_string with func0, "_type"
    Let func0_is_function be proc string_equals from StringCore with func0_type, "llvm_function"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function node _type is llvm_function", func0_is_function, 1

    Let func0_name be proc hir_dict_get_string with func0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "function name is '@add'", func0_name, "@add"

    Let func0_ret be proc hir_dict_get_string with func0, "return_type"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "function return type is 'i32'", func0_ret, "i32"

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: basic block 'entry' ---
    Let bbs1 be proc hir_dict_get with func0, "basic_blocks"
    Let bb_count1 be proc hir_list_count with bbs1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "function has 1 basic block", bb_count1, 1

    Let bb0 be proc hir_list_at with bbs1, 0
    Let bb0_label be proc hir_dict_get_string with bb0, "label"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "basic block label is 'entry'", bb0_label, "entry"

    Note: --- Stage 1 content: instructions (%r = add i32 %a, %b ; ret i32 %r) ---
    Let insts1 be proc hir_dict_get with bb0, "instructions"
    Let inst_count1 be proc hir_list_count with insts1
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "basic block has 2 instructions", inst_count1, 2

    Let add_instr be proc hir_list_at with insts1, 0
    Let add_opcode be proc hir_dict_get_string with add_instr, "opcode"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instruction[0] opcode is 'add'", add_opcode, "add"

    Let add_result be proc hir_dict_get_string with add_instr, "result"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instruction[0] result is '%r'", add_result, "%r"

    Let add_ops be proc hir_dict_get with add_instr, "operands"
    Let add_op_count be proc hir_list_count with add_ops
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "add has 3 operands (type + 2 values)", add_op_count, 3

    Let add_op0 be proc hir_list_at with add_ops, 0
    Let add_op0_val be proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with add_op0
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "add operand[0] type is 'i32'", add_op0_val, "i32"

    Let add_op1 be proc hir_list_at with add_ops, 1
    Let add_op1_val be proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with add_op1
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "add operand[1] is '%a'", add_op1_val, "%a"

    Let add_op2 be proc hir_list_at with add_ops, 2
    Let add_op2_val be proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with add_op2
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "add operand[2] is '%b'", add_op2_val, "%b"

    Let ret_instr be proc hir_list_at with insts1, 1
    Let ret_opcode be proc hir_dict_get_string with ret_instr, "opcode"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "instruction[1] opcode is 'ret'", ret_opcode, "ret"

    Let ret_ops be proc hir_dict_get with ret_instr, "operands"
    Let ret_op_count be proc hir_list_count with ret_ops
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "ret has 2 operands (type + value)", ret_op_count, 2

    Let ret_op0 be proc hir_list_at with ret_ops, 0
    Let ret_op0_val be proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with ret_op0
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "ret operand[0] type is 'i32'", ret_op0_val, "i32"

    Let ret_op1 be proc hir_list_at with ret_ops, 1
    Let ret_op1_val be proc get_string_literal_value from HIR with ret_op1
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "ret operand[1] is '%r'", ret_op1_val, "%r"

    Note: --- Stage 2: HIR -> LLVM IR text ---
    Let emitted be proc generate_llvmir from LlvmBackend with hir1
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "backend produced LLVM IR text", emitted
    Let emitted_len be proc string_length from StringCore with emitted
    proc assert_greater_than from TestUtils with results, "emitted LLVM IR is non-empty", emitted_len, 0

    Note: --- Stage 3: re-parse the emitted text -> HIR (the SECOND emission),
    Note: then assert the section streams are structurally equal. This is the
    Note: load-bearing round-trip assertion. ---
    Let hir2 be proc llvmir_source_to_hir with emitted
    proc assert_not_null from TestUtils with results, "re-parse of emitted LLVM IR produced HIR", hir2

    Let type_value2 be proc hir_dict_get_string with hir2, "_type"
    Let type_is_module2 be proc string_equals from StringCore with type_value2, "llvm_module"
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed HIR _type is llvm_module", type_is_module2, 1

    Let functions2 be proc hir_dict_get with hir2, "functions"
    Let func_count2 be proc hir_list_count with functions2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "re-parsed preserves 1 function", func_count2, 1

    Note: Spot-check survival on the SECOND emission directly (not just stage 1).
    Let r_func0 be proc hir_list_at with functions2, 0
    Let r_func0_name be proc hir_dict_get_string with r_func0, "name"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip function name survives", r_func0_name, "@add"

    Let r_bbs be proc hir_dict_get with r_func0, "basic_blocks"
    Let r_bb0 be proc hir_list_at with r_bbs, 0
    Let r_bb0_label be proc hir_dict_get_string with r_bb0, "label"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip basic block label survives", r_bb0_label, "entry"

    Let r_insts be proc hir_dict_get with r_bb0, "instructions"
    Let r_inst0 be proc hir_list_at with r_insts, 0
    Let r_inst0_op be proc hir_dict_get_string with r_inst0, "opcode"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip add opcode survives", r_inst0_op, "add"
    Let r_inst0_res be proc hir_dict_get_string with r_inst0, "result"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip add result survives", r_inst0_res, "%r"

    Let r_inst1 be proc hir_list_at with r_insts, 1
    Let r_inst1_op be proc hir_dict_get_string with r_inst1, "opcode"
    proc assert_string_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip ret opcode survives", r_inst1_op, "ret"

    Note: --- Full structural equality across the function stream ---
    Let funcs_equal be proc function_streams_equal with functions1, functions2
    proc assert_equal from TestUtils with results, "round-trip functions structurally equal", funcs_equal, 1

    proc print_summary from TestUtils with results
    Let failed be proc get_failed from TestUtils with results
    proc destroy_test_results from TestUtils with results

    Return failed
End Process
